AGI - It will be his longest and most articulated apostolic journey: four states on two continents. Pope Francis, at 87 years old, is not allowed to be conditioned by the attacks of age and has decided to go in the first days of September in Indonesia, Papua New Guinea, East Timor and Singapore. "Welcoming the invitation of the respective heads of state and ecclesiastical authorities - announced this morning the director of the press room of the Holy See Matteo Bruni -, Pope Francis will make an apostolic journey to Indonesia, Papua New Guinea, Timor-Leste and Singapore from September 2 to 13, going to Jakarta from September 3 to 6, to Port Moresby and Vanimo from September 6 to 9, to Dili from September 9 to September 11, and September 13.
The programme confirms the announcements already circulated by individual States. A definitely challenging journey to which however Bergoglio does not want to give up, confirming the great attention he has for Asia.
<div </div
&nbsp;
Three of the countries - Indonesia, Papua New Guinea and East Timor - are the same as Francis should have visited in 2020. Journey then canceled because of the pandemic.
But now Singapore has also been added, a great crossroads of Southeast Asia and - as was Mongolia last year - another privileged place to speak to the people and Chinese culture, being three quarters of its Chinese ethnic population. In recent months it was hoped for a further stage in Vietnam, given the steps made in the relations between Hanoi and the Holy See but, as it is also demonstrating the visit in these days of Monsignor Paul Richard Gallagher, Vatican Secretary for Relations with States, the country for now remains out.
The most detailed programme will be announced in the coming days.
For Indonesia, the largest Muslim country in the world by number of believers, the one scheduled for September will be the third visit of a Pontiff. The first Pope to travel to the archipelago was Paul VI, who on December 3, 1970, on the last of his international apostolic journeys, stopped in Jakarta where he was warmly welcomed by the then President Suharto. From 8 to 12 October 1989 Pope John Paul II went to Indonesia for a trip that was marked by the outdoor Mass at the Jakarta Stadium, and from the stages in Medan, in the north of Sumatra, in Yogyakarta, in the center of Java and Flores, in the eastern Nusa Tenggara.
On that same journey Wojtyla also traveled to Dili, in what was then still the Indonesian province of East Timor. And just the arrival of Francis in East Timor will be a very important moment. The country is the only country, along with the Philippines, by a Catholic majority in Asia and gained its independence only in 2002, after so much blood and suffering. The city-state of Singapore, by Buddhist majority, is the fourth major financial center in the world, second most densely populated country after the Principality of Monaco. In 2009 he reached the highest concentration of millionaires in relation to the population, exceeding Hong Kong, Switzerland, Qatar and Kuwait.&nbsp;
