AGI - "I'm an Italian who had to do it as a clandestine to reach his country." Michel Ivo Ceresoli>, born 34 years ago in Guinea Conakry from the union between an Italian man and a young man of the place but only a few days has managed to obtain a document that attests to all effects his "Italian nationality". The same which is evident already clearly from the surname that it brings, Ceresoli, that of the man who in 1989 marries a young Guinean woman from whom he has two sons, Michel Ivo and Abraham, today thirty years old. The man, originally from Modena, at the time director of the works for the Astaldi society that is carrying out the road Mamou-Kissidougou>, recognizes both children. Then in 1996 he left Guinea and from that moment neither his wife nor his children have more news. For Michel Ivo, who lives in a small village of Conakry, begins a story of double discrimination: that of the Guineans who do not consider it one of them but an 'mezzo italiano' and that of the Italians who ignore his requests for recognition of nationality and deny him the visa to come to Italy. That is then the dream cultivated for 34 years by Michel Ivo, years during which however the young man graduated in international law at the 'Nongo Conakry University', while his brother graduated from the Koffi Anan University of Guinea in tourism.
<h2> A story of double discrimination
"Paradosally - says Michel Ivo - in Guinea I have undergone a sort of exclusion for my Italian origins. I wasn't a pure guinea pig and that made me weigh it. I was among the top ten graduates, nine were hired, I didn't because I was an Italian medium and to work they asked me about money." Michel Ivo's attempts to leave hostile Guinea to reach Italy begin in 2006 but his family has no means and then in those years the Italian embassy in Guinea is closed. The offices reopened only in 2018 but the boy is bounced back to the Italian consulate. "We set a set of appointments - he says - that they have never been respected. It seemed like it was a curse to be Italian and I didn't understand why I was treated like this by a representative of my country. Not to mention the problems with the Guinean authorities who, for racism, have rejected everything because we are not Guineans and therefore do not deserve any public service".
&nbsp;
But the young man intends to reach Italy at any cost, "so I decided to use the money saved to take the sea: I was an Italian who tried to go home illegally." He reaches Mali, barges his phone for a ride to the border with the Niger, where the soldiers tear his passport. Without documents it is able to arrive in Algeria and after a thousand faults Tunisia, the place of departure of the barks that arrive in Lampedusa. It tries twice to reach Italy but only to the third attempt, on 4 July 2023, lands on the island; Michel Ivo, who speaks only French, tells the police that he is Italian. Nobody, however, believes and simply writes: Guinea. Two days later he was transferred to the Cara di Isola Capo Rizzuto where, thanks to the police, volunteers working in the center and the Prefecture of Crotone, he finally proved to be Italian. And the Municipality of Calabria releases its identity card, with the words 'nationalized' Italian.' Michel Ivo now wants to meet his father.&nbsp;

